 Kingdom","Waterton, Lincolnshire, England (United Kingdom)":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Waterton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Waterton (Lincs)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Waterton was born about 1300, in Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Baron Reiner de Waterton, was 29 and his mother, Baroness Elizabeth, was 27. He had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with Elizabeth Newmarch. He died in 1353, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 54."},"et":{"Abt 1300–1353":"umbes 1300–1353","1300–1353":"1300–1353","1314–1366":"1314–1366","1324–1410":"1324–1410","1326–Female":"1326–Surnud","1330–1424":"1330–1424","1272–1310":"1272–1310","1275–1316":"1275–1316","1330":"1330","1275":"1275","AFT 1316":"pärast 1316","ABT 1326":"umbes 1326","1272":"1272","1316":"1316","1326":"1326","1424":"1424","1314":"1314","1324":"1324","Abt 1300":"umbes 1300","